after debugging, it seems like logf fails because of the inclusion of stack-protector-guard. we can verify this by omitting the flag or adding the appropriate __attribute__ guard
for removing stack smashing. specifically, for x86_64 architecture, it seems like the default stack smashing happens via TLS, thread local storage, and uses the segment register %fs or %gs.
since segmentation is mostly ignored in modern 64 bit architectures, most of the segment registers aren't used - except for fs and gs. fs points to special per-cpu data structures in user space,
and gs does the same for the kernel. if we check the disassembly, we see that we do indeed use the %gs register, and that shortly after this a triple fault is carried out - which explains our
boot loop issue.

looking at the qemu log, it seems like what causes the triple fault is RIP=ffffffff8000235a trying to access CR2=000000000000040e, which causes a GPF because the IDT is not setup (IDT=0).

here's the objdump around RIP:
objdump -d kernel/horizon.kernel | grep -B 5 -A 5 "8000235a"
ffffffff80002350 <find_rsdp>:
ffffffff80002350:       f3 0f 1e fa             endbr64
ffffffff80002354:       55                      push   %rbp
ffffffff80002355:       53                      push   %rbx
ffffffff80002356:       48 83 ec 08             sub    $0x8,%rsp

ffffffff8000235a:       0f b7 2c 25 0e 04 00    movzwl 0x40e,%ebp

ffffffff80002361:       00
ffffffff80002362:       c1 e5 04                shl    $0x4,%ebp
ffffffff80002365:       89 eb                   mov    %ebp,%ebx
ffffffff80002367:       81 c5 00 04 00 00       add    $0x400,%ebp
ffffffff8000236d:       48 39 eb                cmp    %rbp,%rbx

it seems like the operation in question is a moczwl of the stack base pointer.

ok, it seems like the code isn't compiling with our architecture flags - whoops. that's a huge oversight on my part. fixed.

we still have issues accessing the rsdp - Limine maps out memory for us, but it looks like base revision 3 (the most up to date). according to the limine protocol:
> "The only memory map regions mapped to the HHDM are: Usable, Bootloader reclaimable, Executable and modules, Framebuffer."
so, we still need to implement full x86_64 paging support ourselves.

# CMake

root file: CMakeLists.txt

can add subdirectories with add_subdirectory(). nested CMakeLists.txt will be used

project() - specify a project.
ex: project(MyOS C CXX ASM)

variables with set(VAR <value>)
message("MY_VAR")

## Control Flow
if(VAR STREQUAL <value>)
    message("yes")
endif()

// SOURCES here is a list of source files
foreach(file ${SOURCES})
    message("file: ${file}")
endforeach()

targets - will include dependencies
add_executable(myprog main.c)


### LINKING
target_include_directories(myprog PRIVATE include/)
target_compile_options(myprog PRIVATE -Wall -Wextra)
target_link_libraries(myprog PRIVATE mylib)
